 Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Tunstall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>tūn-stall</i> ‘site of a farm, farmstead’, notably Tunstall (Lancashire) and one or more of many Staffordshire places (Tunstall near Stoke on Trent, Tunstall near Adbaston, and four places called Dunstall), but also Tunstall Farm in Mountfield (Sussex) and possibly also Tunstall (Durham, Kent, Norfolk, Shropshire, Suffolk, east and North Yorkshire), and Dunstall (Lincolnshire)."],"variants":[{"name":"Tunstill","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Tunstall  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":34,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":43,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas de Tunstall was born about 1181, in Lancashire, England, his father, William de Tunstall I, was 22 and his mother, Maud Tunstall, was 17. He married Maud de Austwick about 1202, in Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1246, in Cantsfield, Lancashire, England, at the age of 67."},"et":{"about 1181–about 1246":"umbes 1181–umbes 1246","1181–1246":"1181–1246","1183–1246":"1183–1246","1205–1246":"1205–1246","–Male":"Surnud","1184–1229":"1184–1229","1200–1246":"1200–1246","1161–1203":"1161–1203","1166–Female":"1166–Surnud","about 1181":"umbes 1181","1184":"1184","1161":"1161","1183":"1183","1181":"1181","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","after 1229":"pärast 1229","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1200":"1200","1166":"1166","about 1202":"umbes 1202","about 1246":"umbes 1246","about 1203":"umbes 1203","about 1200":"umbes 1200","1229":"1229","Tunstall, Lancashire, England":"Tunstall, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Cantsfield, Lancashire, England":"Cantsfield, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"about 1181–about 1246":"noin 1181–noin 1246","1181–1246":"1181–1246","1183–1246":"1183–1246","1205–1246":"1205–1246","–Male":"Kuollut","1184–1229":"1184–1229","1200–1246":"1200–1246","1161–1203":"1161–1203","1166–Female":"1166–Kuollut","about 1181":"noin 1181","1184":"1184","1161":"1161","1183":"1183","1181":"1181","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1203":"1203","after 1229":"1229 jälkeen","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1200":"1200","1166":"1166","about 1202":"noin 1202","about 1246":"noin 1246","about 1203":"noin 1203","about 1200":"noin 1200","1